**Interpretation:**

Both predictors are highly significant. A one-percentage-point increase in the share of non-managers with a college degree is associated with a 0.006-point increase in the management score (95% CI: [0.006, 0.007]). Since the management score ranges from 1 to 5, moving from 0% to 100% non-manager degree coverage would predict a 0.6-point improvement — a meaningful but not transformative effect on the cross-section.

Firm size also predicts higher management quality: a 1% increase in employment is associated with a 0.187-point increase in score (95% CI: [0.178, 0.197]). The overall R² of 0.144 means that education and size together explain about 14% of the cross-sectional variation in management quality.

However, this estimate is of limited causal value. It compares firms in different countries, sectors, and founding eras — all of which affect both workforce education and management quality simultaneously. The pooled OLS coefficient conflates any genuine effect of education with these stable background characteristics. This is OVB.

---

