**The within-R² and what it tells us:**

The overall R² of 0.763–0.767 in the FE models is misleadingly high — it includes all the variance explained by the firm fixed effects themselves (the stable differences between firms). The **within-R²** is the meaningful statistic: it measures how much of the *within-firm* variation in management quality is explained by the time-varying predictors alone. Here it is **0.005–0.006** — just 0.5–0.6%.

This is very low. Does it mean our model is wrong? No — but it means something substantively important: **workforce education and firm size barely change within firms between survey waves**. The WMS surveys the same firm at intervals of several years; in that time, a firm's educational composition shifts slowly. There is simply not much within-unit variation in `degree_nm` to explain management changes.

The upshot: the statistically significant coefficient on `degree_nm` is real, but changes in workforce education explain almost none of the year-to-year management variation we observe within firms. Most within-firm management change is driven by factors not in our model — a new management team, a strategic overhaul, an ownership transition, a new market shock.

**Does a richer model help?** The WMS also contains `degree_m` (the share of managers with a college degree), which arguably matters more directly for management quality. Adding it gives a more complete picture:


::: {.cell}

```{.r .cell-code}
m_fe_ext <- feols(management ~ degree_nm + degree_m + log_emp | firmid,
                  vcov = ~firmid, data = wms)

m_2way_ext <- feols(management ~ degree_nm + degree_m + log_emp | firmid + wave,
                    vcov = ~firmid, data = wms)

modelsummary(
  list(
    "Firm FE (base)"    = m_fe,
    "Firm FE + deg_m"   = m_fe_ext,
    "Two-way FE + deg_m"= m_2way_ext
  ),
  coef_map  = c("degree_nm" = "Degree (non-managers)",
                "degree_m"  = "Degree (managers)",
                "log_emp"   = "Log(employees)"),
  statistic = "conf.int", conf_level = 0.95,
  gof_map   = c("nobs", "r.squared", "r2.within"),
  stars     = TRUE,
  notes     = "SEs clustered at firm level throughout.",
  output    = "flextable"
) |> autofit()
```

