# Optional Extension A — Restricted sample comparison

When comparing pooled OLS (N = 12,793) to firm FE (N = 5,938), two things changed simultaneously: the estimator *and* the sample. Firms observed only once cannot contribute to the within-firm FE estimate and are dropped. If these singleton firms are systematically different — perhaps smaller, less stable, or operating in less regulated markets — the coefficient shift could reflect sample selection rather than the FE correction. Disentangling the two is important for understanding what is actually driving the result.

**Strategy:** run pooled OLS on the FE-eligible firms only (those with ≥ 2 observations), then stack three models side by side:

| Column | Estimator | Sample |
|---|---|---|
| OLS (full) | Pooled OLS | All 12,793 obs |
| OLS (FE sample) | Pooled OLS | FE-eligible firms only |
| Firm FE | Within estimator | FE-eligible firms only |

The OLS (full) → OLS (FE sample) shift isolates the **sample selection effect**. The OLS (FE sample) → Firm FE shift isolates the **genuine FE correction**.


::: {.cell}

```{.r .cell-code}
fe_firms <- wms |>
  count(firmid) |>
  filter(n > 1) |>
  pull(firmid)

wms_fe <- wms |> filter(firmid %in% fe_firms)

m_ols_fe <- feols(management ~ degree_nm + log_emp, data = wms_fe)
```
:::



::: {.cell tbl-cap='Decomposing the coefficient shift: sample selection vs. FE correction. 95% confidence intervals in brackets.'}

```{.r .cell-code}
modelsummary(
  list(
    "OLS (full)"      = m_ols,
    "OLS (FE sample)" = m_ols_fe,
    "Firm FE"         = m_fe
  ),
  coef_map  = c("degree_nm" = "Degree (non-managers)",
                "log_emp"   = "Log(employees)"),
  statistic = "conf.int", conf_level = 0.95,
  gof_map   = c("nobs", "r.squared", "r2.within"),
  stars     = TRUE,
  notes     = c(
    "95% CIs in brackets.",
    "OLS models: HC1 standard errors. Firm FE: clustered at firm level.",
    "OLS (FE sample) restricted to firms observed ≥ 2 times."
  ),
  output    = "flextable"
) |> autofit()
```

